DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260321T130000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260321T150000
SUMMARY:Kiosque de solidarité avec nos voisin.es non logé.es
LOCATION:Métro Pie-Ix
DESCRIPTION:2026-03-21 13:00:00\n\nMétro Pie-Ix\n\nhttps://www.openstreet
 map.org/relation/14023444\n\n(English will follow)\nAprès la réussite du
  kiosque au parc Morgan en décembre dernier\, le collectif Entrave (annon
 ce publique à venir) a décidé de le reproduire tout l'hiver\, le troisi
 ème samedi du mois jusqu'en avril.\nLes Hochelagais.es\, logé.es ou non\
 , sont venu.es en nombre pour donner ou pour recevoir du matériel nécess
 aire pour survivre l'hiver.\nVenez samedi prochain\, de 13h à 17h\, discu
 ter de notre monde commun\, manger un repas et boire un chocolat chauds pr
 éparés par @les.greniers.agricoles.qc .\nÀ samedi!\n*Liste de matériel
  (accessible avec le code QR):\n- matériel de camping (cordes\, piquets\,
  bashes)\n- sacs de couchage\n- tentes\n- matelas/oreillers\n- couvertures
 &nbsp\;\n- réservoirs de propane\n- bottes/souliers (besoin de grandes ta
 illes)\n- vêtements chauds (chandails manches longues\, gants\, foulards\
 , tuques\, combines\, etc.)\n- chaussettes&nbsp\;\n- des "pads" chauffants
 \n- lingettes nettoyantes (désinfectantes ou pour le corps)\n- gel hydroa
 lcoolique\n- matériel de premiers soins&nbsp\;\n- matériel de réduction
  des risques liés à la consommation\n- bougies\n- lampes de poche\n- bat
 teries AA ou AAA&nbsp\;\n---\nFollowing the success of the kiosk at Morgan
  Park last December\, the Entrave collective (public announcement to follo
 w) has decided to repeat the initiative throughout the winter\, on the thi
 rd Saturday of each month until April.\nHochelaga residents\, both homeles
 s and housed\, came out in large numbers to give or receive the supplies t
 hey need to survive the winter.\nCome next Saturday\, from 1:00 p.m. to 5:
 00 p.m.\, to discuss our shared world\, enjoy a meal and hot chocolate pre
 pared by @les.greniers.agricoles.qc .\nSee you Saturday!\n*List of supplie
 s needed (accessible with the QR code):\n- Camping equipment (ropes\, stak
 es\, bashes)\n- Sleeping bags\n- Tents\n- Mattresses/pillows\n- Blankets&n
 bsp\;\n- Propane tanks\n- Boots/shoes (large sizes needed)\n- Warm clothin
 g (long-sleeved sweaters\, gloves\, scarves\, hats\, snowsuits\, etc.)\n- 
 socks\n- heating pads\n- cleaning wipes (disinfectant or body wipes)\n- ha
 nd sanitizer\n- first aid supplies\n- substance use risk reduction supplie
 s\n- candles\n- flashlights\n- AA or AAA batteries\n&nbsp\;
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.openstreetmap.org/relation/14023444
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:resmtl-54
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTAMP:20260310T034710
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260321T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260321T160000
SUMMARY:Manif pour un statut pour toutes et tous !
LOCATION:1200 St-Laurent (métro St-Laurent)
DESCRIPTION:2026-03-21 14:00:00\n\n1200 St-Laurent (métro St-Laurent)\n\n
 https://www.openstreetmap.org/node/12034339159\n\nDown with Racist attacks
  against Migrants: Yes to Regularization! No to the Safe Third Country Agr
 eement! Here to stay!\nSaturday\, February 21 at 2 p.m.\nMinistry of Immig
 ration of Quebec\n1200 Saint-Laurent Boulevard (Saint-Laurent metro statio
 n)\nfacebook\nFamily-friendly: bring your children!\nEveryone is welcome a
 t our demonstrations\, especially people with precarious immigration statu
 s. We are aware of the fear and real risks faced by undocumented migrants 
 and we try to organize our demonstrations in a way that is as safe as poss
 ible for everyone. If you are afraid to attend because of your status\, pl
 ease contact us and we can discuss.\nJoin us in front of the Quebec Minist
 ry of Immigration (MIFI) offices in Montreal to denounce the rise of xenop
 hobia in Quebec and its long list of anti-immigrant policies: the closure 
 of Roxham Road to refugees in transit to the United States\, the intermina
 ble delays for CSQs (required for regularization in Quebec) for undocument
 ed immigrants\, the suspension of family sponsorship programs\, cuts to so
 cial programs for refugee families\, the end of pilot projects for working
  class temporary foreign workers\, the end of the Quebec Experience Progra
 m (PEQ)\, and the hardening anti-immigrant rhetoric. These policies plunge
  migrants into even more desperate situations of exploitation and precarit
 y in Quebec’s fields\, factories\, and hospitals. We reject these violen
 t attacks and unite to demand permanent status for all. We fight for our f
 reedom to exist\, to move\, and to stay\, in all dignity and equality.\nSo
 lidarity Across Borders has been fighting for migrant justice for over 20 
 years in Tiohtiake/Montreal\, and the PEQ saga is nothing new for those ne
 wly arrived in so-called Quebec. From those who don’t share “Quebec va
 lues” to the guardian angels of the pandemic\, the CAQ has seized every 
 opportunity to deify or demonize immigrants for electoral gain. Most recen
 tly\, the noise made by the CAQ leadership candidates and Minister Roberge
  over the PEQ grandfather clause demonstrates just how performative and un
 popular their populist tactics are. Their ridiculous management of immigra
 tion has real and devastating consequences for many people\, regardless of
  the migration paths open to them. Unfortunately\, a grandfather clause wi
 ll not stop the invisibilization or criminalization of people with precari
 ous and temporary status by governments. We must understand the issue of p
 recarious migration holistically. It is imperative that we unite in solida
 rity with all undocumented and precarious migrants to demand an inclusive 
 regularization program and permanent residency for all. Everyone deserves 
 dignity\, not because of our skills\, but because we are human beings firs
 t and foremost.\nWe call on all people with legal status to oppose the ant
 i-migrant measures and rhetoric of their governments. We call on our allie
 s to reject the “good” and “bad” migrant narratives that reinforce
  global apartheid and the brutal border system.\nTogether in solidarity\, 
 strong and proud\, let us unite to demand a continuous and inclusive progr
 am of full regularization for all undocumented and precarious status migra
 nts\, as well as an end to the Safe Third Country Agreement.
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.openstreetmap.org/node/12034339159
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:resmtl-55
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTAMP:20260310T034710
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260321T150000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260321T170000
SUMMARY:Violet Hour Book Club : "The Tiger and the Cosmonaut"
LOCATION:6450 avenue Christophe-Colomb
DESCRIPTION:2026-03-21 15:00:00\n\n6450 avenue Christophe-Colomb\n\nhttps:
 //www.openstreetmap.org/way/1080082859\n\nJoin us for the next meeting of 
 the Violet Hour Book Club\, a reading group devoted to classic and contemp
 orary works of LGBTQ literature. The book we will be discussing is The Tig
 er and the Cosmonaut (2025) by Eddy Boudel Tan.\nToustes sont invités·es
  au Violet Hour Book Club\, et chacun.e est bienvenu.e à partager ses pen
 sées sur le livre en anglais ou en français.\nWe will be meeting at Espa
 ce des Possibles Petite-Patrie (6450 Avenue Christophe Colomb\, Beaubien M
 etro). L’Espace des Possibles a comme mission d’offrir un lieu d’ent
 raide\, d’apprentissages et d’implication dédié à la transition soc
 iale et écologique (la transition socio-écologique).\nThe space is given
  to us for free\, but VHBC participants are welcome to make voluntary cont
 ributions to help support our mandate to create LGBTQ literary events for 
 Montrealers.\nA reminder: All VHBC titles are available at Librairie Parag
 raphe Bookstore (2220\, McGill College Ave) at 15% off and at Librairie Pu
 lp Books &amp\; Cafe (3952 Wellington St.) at 10% off.\nABOUT THE BOOK ///
 \nA noirish page-turner about a mysterious disappearance and a moving port
 rait of a Chinese Canadian family navigating insecurities\, expectations\,
  and simmering anger in their small BC town.\nCasper Han grew up the dutif
 ul son of immigrants who never felt entirely welcome in their remote corne
 r of British Columbia. Now an adult\, living in Vancouver with a boyfriend
  whose privilege he quietly resents\, Casper rarely returns to his hometow
 n\, the site of a grief his family doesn’t discuss: the loss of his twin
  brother\, Sam.\nOver twenty years have passed since Sam went missing\, an
 d a crisis brings Casper and his siblings back. Their father has vanished\
 , only to be found wandering the vast woods beyond the family home\, confu
 sed and clutching a pair of scissors\, seemingly trapped in the memory of 
 that tragic night. In order to move forward\, the Han family must finally 
 confront the past and untangle the mystery of what really happened to Sam.
 \nCombining the atmosphere and intrigue of a cracking good suspense novel 
 with the depth of a rich character study\, The Tiger and the Cosmonaut tel
 ls the story of a family whose members have long made themselves small and
  quiet and obedient—and what happens when the cycle is finally broken.\n
 &nbsp\;
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/1080082859
END:VEVENT
